<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<worksheet>
  <title>Section 4.2. - Finding eigenvectors and eigenvalues</title>
  <objectives>
    <introduction>
      <p>\begin{enumerate}



\item How do we know if the eigenvectors of an <m>n\times n</m> matrix form a basis for <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>?

\end{enumerate}</p>
    </introduction>
  </objectives>
  <introduction>
    <p>\\</p>
    <p>If <m>A</m> is an <m>m\times m</m> matrix, we would like to know if there is a
basis of <m>\real^m</m> consisting of eigenvectors of <m>A</m>.</p>
    <p>Remember:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p>The eigenvalues of <m>A</m> are the roots of the charactertic
  polynomial <m>\det(A-\lambda I) = 0</m>.</p></li>
      <li><p>The set of eigenvectors associated to <m>\lambda</m> forms the
  eigenspace <m>E_\lambda</m>, which is the solution space of the equation
  <m>(A-\lambda I)\xvec=\zerovec</m> or, in other words,
  <m>E_\lambda = \nul(A-\lambda I)</m>.</p></li>
    </ul>
    <p><term>Handy:</term>Here's a handy Sage command.  If <c>A</c> is a square matrix,
  then <c>A.fcp('x')</c> will tell you the ``factored characteristic
  polynomial'' expressed in terms of a variable <c>x</c>.</p>
  </introduction>

  <exercise>
    <introduction>
      <p>Consider the matrix
  <m>\begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp -1 \\ 4 \amp -4 \\ \end{bmatrix}</m>.</p>
    </introduction>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>What is its
  factored characteristic polynomial?</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>What are the eigenvalues of <m>A</m>?</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="2in">
      <statement>
        <p>Find a basis for each eigenspace of this matrix.  What is the
  dimension of each eigenspace?</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>Is there a basis
  of <m>\real^2</m> consisting of eigenvectors?  If so, what is one such basis?</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
  </exercise>

  <exercise workspace=".7in">
    <introduction>
      <p>Consider the matrix
  <md>
  A = \begin{bmatrix}
    -1 \amp 0 \amp 2 \\
    -2 \amp -2 \amp -4 \\
    0 \amp 0 \amp -2 \\
  \end{bmatrix}.
  </md></p>
    </introduction>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>Find factored characteristic polynomial of <m>A</m>.</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="3in">
      <statement>
        <p>For each eigenvalue, find a basis for its associated eigenspace and
  state its dimension.</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>Is there a basis for <m>\real^3</m> consisting of eigenvectors of <m>A</m>?</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <introduction>
      <p>Now consider the matrix
  <md>
  B = \begin{bmatrix}
    -5 \amp -2 \amp -6 \\
    -2 \amp -2 \amp -4 \\
    2 \amp 1 \amp 2 \\
  \end{bmatrix}.
  </md></p>
    </introduction>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>Find factored characteristic polynomial of <m>B</m>.</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="3in">
      <statement>
        <p>For each eigenvalue, find a basis for its associated eigenspace and
  its dimension.</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>Is there a basis for <m>\real^3</m> consisting of eigenvectors of <m>B</m>?
  If so, what is one such basis?</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
  </exercise>

  <exercise workspace="1in">
    <introduction>
      <p>Remember that the determinant of a triangular matrix, such as
  <m>
  A =
  \begin{bmatrix}
    2 \amp -4 \amp -19 \\
    0 \amp 4 \amp 7 \\
    0 \amp 0 \amp -3
  \end{bmatrix}
  </m>,
  is the product of the diagonal entries.</p>
    </introduction>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>What does this say about
  the eigenvalues of a triangular matrix?</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>What are the eigenvalues of this matrix <m>A</m>?</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="3in">
      <statement>
        <p>Find a basis for each of the eigenspaces and state their dimensions.</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>Is there a basis of <m>\real^3</m> consisting of eigenvectors of <m>A</m>?</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
  </exercise>

  <exercise workspace="1in">
    <statement>
      <p>Suppose that the factored characteristic polynomial of a matrix
  <m>C</m> is
  <md>(2-\lambda)(4-\lambda)(6-\lambda)(13-\lambda).
  </md>
  If <m>C</m> is an <m>m\times m</m> matrix, what is <m>m</m>?</p>
      <p>Based on the examples we've seen, do you think there will be a basis
  of <m>\real^m</m> consisting
  of eigenvectors of <m>C</m></p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

</worksheet>
